  "prompt": "What should I do if my best friend's friend likes me but I like my best friend?",
  "response": "Navigating feelings in friendships can be tricky, especially when there's a triangle of emotions involved. Here are some steps you can take to address the situation:\n\n1. **Clarify Your Feelings**: Reflect on your feelings for your best friend. Make sure you understand what you're feeling and what you want out of the relationship.\n\n2. **Consider the Other Person's Feelings**: Think about your best friend's friend who likes you. It\u2019s important to be respectful of their feelings while also being true to your own.\n\n3. **Talk to Your Best Friend**: If you feel comfortable, consider discussing your feelings with your best friend. Be honest about your feelings for them and how you value your friendship.\n\n4. **Set Boundaries**: If you decide to pursue a relationship with your best friend, it may be necessary to set clear boundaries with their friend to avoid any potential misunderstandings or hurt feelings.\n\n5. **Communicate with Their Friend**: If their friend expresses interest in you, you can kindly explain that you're not interested in them romantically because your feelings are directed toward someone else.\n\n6. **Be Kind but Firm**: It's crucial to be kind but firm in your approach. Clear communication can help prevent any misinterpretations of your feelings.\n\n7. **Focus on Your Feelings**: Ultimately, prioritize the relationship that feels right for you. Pursuing a romantic relationship with your best friend may feel more fulfilling than leading someone else on.\n\nRemember that friendships can be complicated, but honesty and communication are key to navigating these situations. Good luck!",
